ased","1347–1403":"1347–1403","1349–1392":"1349–1392","1240–1285":"1240–1285","1254–Female":"1254–Deceased","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1392":"1392","1280":"1280","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1403":"1403","1347":"1347","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1254":"1254","about 1300":"about 1300","Hipswell, Richmondshire, North Yorkshire, England":"Hipswell, Yorkshire, England","Fulthorpe, Darlington, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Darlington, Durham, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Hipswell, Yorkshire, England":"Hipswell, Yorkshire, England","Fulthorpe, Darlington, Durham, England":"Darlington, Durham, England, United Kingdom","Saint Mary's the Virgin Churchyard, Norton, Stockton-on-Tees Unitary Authority, County Durham, England":"Norton, Durham, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Fulthorpe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Fulthorpe in Grindon by Stockton on Tees (Durham)."],"variants":[{"name":"Fulthorp","meanings":["English:  see  Fulthorpe  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Roger de Fulthorpe was born in 1285, in Hipswell, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Adam de Fulthorpe, was 45 and his mother, Lady Lillit de Sombrom, was 31. He had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Lady Alice le Blount. He died in 1337, at the age of 52, and was buried in Norton, Durham, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1285–1337":"1285–1337","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1300–1356":"1300–1356","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1347–1403":"1347–1403","1349–1392":"1349–1392","1240–1285":"1240–1285","1254–Female":"1254–Surnud","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1392":"1392","1280":"1280","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1403":"1403","1347":"1347","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1254":"1254","about 1300":"umbes 1300","Hipswell, Richmondshire, North Yorkshire, England":"Hipswell, Yorkshire, England","Fulthorpe, Darlington, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Darlington, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hipswell, Yorkshire, England":"Hipswell, Yorkshire, England","Fulthorpe, Darlington, Durham, England":"Darlington, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Saint Mary's the Virgin Churchyard, N